00:11:41.400 --> 00:11:42.333
this summer.

00:11:43.233 --> 00:11:43.633
Um, but...

00:11:43.633 --> 00:11:47.200
very slow at first, yeah.

00:11:47.300 --> 00:11:48.500
Um, like—

00:11:48.500 --> 00:11:49.100
you know, the sort of

00:11:49.100 --> 00:11:53.800
classic S-curve ramp of manufacturing units versus time.

00:11:54.633 --> 00:11:56.166
Um, and then...

00:11:56.233 --> 00:11:56.866
probably

00:11:56.866 --> 00:12:01.133
reach high-volume production around summer next year, uh...

00:12:02.300 --> 00:12:03.400
and then, um...

00:12:04.833 --> 00:12:07.166
you know, we'll have Optimus 4.

00:12:08.700 --> 00:12:11.666
You know, the design could be next year.

00:12:11.800 --> 00:12:14.900
Like, I try to release a new robot design every year

00:12:14.966 --> 00:12:17.066
and improve robot design every year.

00:12:17.200 --> 00:12:20.200
When Dave Blundin and I were at the Gigafactory,

00:12:20.200 --> 00:12:21.766
it was an extraordinary experience.

00:12:21.766 --> 00:12:24.166
Eleven and a half million square feet for Tesla,

00:12:24.166 --> 00:12:25.400
and then I think you said

00:12:25.400 --> 00:12:26.166
you're building out

00:12:26.166 --> 00:12:29.200
nine and a half million square feet for Optimus there

00:12:29.200 --> 00:12:30.633
as well, which is, uh...

00:12:30.633 --> 00:12:31.766
which is extraordinary.

00:12:32.400 --> 00:12:33.800
Um, let's—

00:12:33.800 --> 00:12:35.033
let's call it ten million square feet,

00:12:35.033 --> 00:12:36.566
round numbers, yeah.

00:12:36.800 --> 00:12:37.866
Yeah, yeah.

00:12:37.866 --> 00:12:38.833
Yeah, that'll be—

00:12:38.833 --> 00:12:40.233
that'll be quite the—

00:12:40.233 --> 00:12:41.800
that's going to be a—

00:12:42.433 --> 00:12:44.966
a new factory design too.

00:12:44.966 --> 00:12:47.400
It's different from other factories.

00:12:48.633 --> 00:12:51.933
How far away are we from having robots building robots?

00:12:52.033 --> 00:12:55.200
I mean, you've automated so much of the Gigafactory already,

00:12:55.666 --> 00:12:58.466
where humans are playing a small role.

00:12:58.766 --> 00:13:00.466
Do the robots just play the role

00:13:00.466 --> 00:13:02.200
that humans are playing in that regard?

00:13:04.700 --> 00:13:07.100
Uh, we still have a lot of humans building things.

00:13:07.200 --> 00:13:08.100
Mm-hmm, um...

00:13:08.666 --> 00:13:11.633
You know, Tesla direct employees who are, uh...

00:13:11.633 --> 00:13:12.766
...building things,

00:13:12.766 --> 00:13:13.666
or, basically,

00:13:13.666 --> 00:13:15.066
people in the factory are either building

00:13:15.066 --> 00:13:16.766
or managing people who are building.

00:13:17.300 --> 00:13:19.300
It's roughly a hundred thousand.

00:13:20.666 --> 00:13:22.000
So we have a lot of people.

00:13:22.066 --> 00:13:24.033
The total headcount is

00:13:24.033 --> 00:13:25.300
around 150K,

00:13:25.466 --> 00:13:27.900
of which two-thirds are, you know,

00:13:27.900 --> 00:13:29.700
in the factory in one form or another.

00:13:29.700 --> 00:13:32.000
And then our suppliers—there's probably

00:13:32.966 --> 00:13:36.833
maybe a million or two million people at our suppliers,

00:13:36.833 --> 00:13:38.600
type of thing. So it's a lot of people.

00:13:41.266 --> 00:13:42.400
What we do expect, though,

00:13:42.400 --> 00:13:45.266
is that the output per

00:13:45.666 --> 00:13:48.433
person at Tesla becomes very,

00:13:48.433 --> 00:13:49.733
very high, yeah.

00:13:49.966 --> 00:13:51.233
So we're not planning any

00:13:51.233 --> 00:13:53.366
layoffs or reductions in personnel.

00:13:53.366 --> 00:13:56.266
In fact, we will increase our headcount, um...

00:13:56.700 --> 00:13:57.200
But...

00:13:57.200 --> 00:14:01.566
the output per human at Tesla is going to get insanely high.

00:14:03.266 --> 00:14:05.666
I mean, you won't freaking believe it.

00:14:05.666 --> 00:14:08.066
Yeah, when we were together, um...

00:14:08.433 --> 00:14:11.400
we discussed the idea of sustainable abundance

00:14:11.633 --> 00:14:12.966
on our podcast, and...

00:14:12.966 --> 00:14:14.300
you reinforced the idea

00:14:14.300 --> 00:14:15.966
that we have a coming age of universal

00:14:15.966 --> 00:14:17.633
high income, uh...

00:14:17.633 --> 00:14:21.466
which has become a point of discussion beyond UBI.

00:14:21.633 --> 00:14:22.366
But I'm just wondering

00:14:22.366 --> 00:14:25.700
if you have any thoughts on how we get there.

00:14:25.766 --> 00:14:29.166
Have you reflected on that any further? And

00:14:29.166 --> 00:14:30.700
more so, you know,

00:14:30.700 --> 00:14:33.833
we talked about a time frame of civil unrest—

00:14:33.833 --> 00:14:34.666
you know, two,

00:14:34.666 --> 00:14:35.166
three, four,

00:14:35.166 --> 00:14:36.666
five years, uh...

00:14:36.666 --> 00:14:39.633
probably a lot of COVID-like

00:14:39.633 --> 00:14:43.333
checks in the interim until we get to a demonetization—

00:14:43.666 --> 00:14:44.666
uh, and a...

00:14:44.666 --> 00:14:47.800
you know, deflation that leads us to UHI.

00:14:47.866 --> 00:14:49.200
Any more reflections on that?

00:14:49.200 --> 00:14:49.766
Because it's really—

00:14:49.766 --> 00:14:51.600
people need that hope and that vision.

00:14:54.700 --> 00:14:55.400
Yeah, I...

00:14:55.400 --> 00:14:56.100
I mean, to be clear, I...

00:14:56.100 --> 00:14:58.466
I don't think we should be sort of complacent.

00:14:58.466 --> 00:14:59.766
We do need to be careful,

00:14:59.766 --> 00:15:03.200
because the future is a range of possible outcomes, and...

00:15:03.200 --> 00:15:04.833
they're not all great.

00:15:04.833 --> 00:15:06.466
Um, but I...

00:15:06.466 --> 00:15:07.500
at this point, I...

00:15:07.500 --> 00:15:09.066
I do agree with you that it's

00:15:09.066 --> 00:15:12.000
likely to be great, um...

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:13.433
You know, it's probably 80% likely—

00:15:13.433 --> 00:15:15.166
maybe more likely—to be great.

00:15:15.666 --> 00:15:16.700
And, uh...

00:15:17.666 --> 00:15:19.700
I do think we'll have universal high income.

00:15:19.700 --> 00:15:22.166
We'll basically just issue money to people,

00:15:22.366 --> 00:15:23.266
you know, and...

00:15:23.266 --> 00:15:25.333
and the idea really is, uh...

00:15:26.700 --> 00:15:28.866
because the output of goods and services will far,

00:15:28.866 --> 00:15:32.333
so far exceed the money supply that, um...

00:15:33.866 --> 00:15:35.066
you know, that...

00:15:35.066 --> 00:15:36.633
effectively, you have deflation.

00:15:36.633 --> 00:15:37.500
Because deflation

00:15:37.500 --> 00:15:39.833
is just the ratio of the output of goods and services

00:15:39.833 --> 00:15:40.866
to the money supply.

00:15:42.233 --> 00:15:43.400
Um, so that—

00:15:43.400 --> 00:15:44.833
that's—so if—

00:15:44.833 --> 00:15:48.566
if the rate of growth of goods and services

00:15:48.566 --> 00:15:50.100
exceeds the rate of growth of the money supply,

00:15:50.100 --> 00:15:51.366
which I predict will happen,

00:15:52.033 --> 00:15:52.900
then, uh...

00:15:53.033 --> 00:15:54.500
you will have deflation.

00:15:55.400 --> 00:15:57.666
Yes, and a lot of—

00:15:57.666 --> 00:16:00.000
a lot of people spinning up new companies,

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:01.000
competing against each other,

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:03.566
driving the price down and increasing the availability—

00:16:03.900 --> 00:16:07.100
and deflation faster and faster.

00:16:07.666 --> 00:16:09.200
Yeah, it's basically—

00:16:09.200 --> 00:16:10.866
AI and robots are going to make so much stuff

00:16:10.866 --> 00:16:13.600
and provide so many services that, uh...

00:16:13.700 --> 00:16:14.300
they will actually

00:16:14.300 --> 00:16:17.300
run out of things to do for humans.

00:16:18.866 --> 00:16:20.400
They'll just run out of things to do for humans,

00:16:20.400 --> 00:16:21.966
and then, well...

00:16:22.033 --> 00:16:22.833
you know,

00:16:23.300 --> 00:16:25.900
there's only so much that humans can even express

00:16:25.900 --> 00:16:26.966
that they want.

00:16:27.766 --> 00:16:29.466
So you go back to my example of, like,

00:16:29.466 --> 00:16:32.100
if you go a million times greater than the U.S. economy,

00:16:33.166 --> 00:16:37.933
you've long since saturated all human desire.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:41.033
Uh, you know...

00:16:41.033 --> 00:16:42.233
like, maybe,

00:16:42.233 --> 00:16:43.600
like if you go

00:16:43.600 --> 00:16:45.866
a thousand times beyond our current economy—

00:16:45.866 --> 00:16:47.500
a thousand times—

00:16:47.500 --> 00:16:49.466
you've probably already saturated

00:16:49.466 --> 00:16:50.700
human—

00:16:50.700 --> 00:16:52.400
anything people can think of that they want.

00:16:53.100 --> 00:16:54.866
So do you think the—

00:16:54.866 --> 00:16:58.033
the value of money is going to significantly decrease?

00:16:58.033 --> 00:17:00.133
Will we go post-capitalist?

00:17:04.233 --> 00:17:07.500
Yeah, I think money will stop being relevant

00:17:07.500 --> 00:17:08.900
at some point in the future.

00:17:09.233 --> 00:17:10.800
So just as you're becoming a—

00:17:11.166 --> 00:17:14.633
It's probably something like an Iain M. Banks,

00:17:14.633 --> 00:17:17.066
Culture sort of future, um...

00:17:18.300 --> 00:17:21.900
And I think the AI down the road will really

00:17:23.433 --> 00:17:25.166
not use, uh...

00:17:25.166 --> 00:17:27.766
human currency. It will just care about, uh...

00:17:28.166 --> 00:17:30.200
power and mass, wattage and tonnage.

00:17:31.300 --> 00:17:33.266
It's kind of ironic then, right?

00:17:33.266 --> 00:17:36.066
Just as you're becoming a multi-trillionaire,

00:17:36.066 --> 00:17:38.200
money starts to have less value, um...

00:17:41.266 --> 00:17:43.766
Yeah, pretty much, um...

00:17:45.766 --> 00:17:47.166
Uh, yeah.

00:17:47.400 --> 00:17:49.000
You know, all this stuff—

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:50.566
it's really just...

00:17:50.566 --> 00:17:51.400
it just represents, like,

00:17:51.400 --> 00:17:54.466
some percentage ownership in companies that I...

00:17:54.466 --> 00:17:55.466
you know, built.

00:17:55.466 --> 00:17:58.400
And it's not like it's sitting in a bank account.

00:17:58.400 --> 00:17:59.566
You know, it's just literally—

00:17:59.566 --> 00:18:00.766
I own a percentage of the companies.

00:18:00.766 --> 00:18:02.766
The companies are doing lots of useful things.

00:18:02.766 --> 00:18:04.700
The value of the company grows.

00:18:04.700 --> 00:18:05.900
I own a percentage of the companies,

00:18:05.900 --> 00:18:08.166
and that sums up to that number,

00:18:08.166 --> 00:18:10.066
which seems high, yeah.

00:18:10.066 --> 00:18:11.100
You know, it's—

00:18:11.100 --> 00:18:13.566
I was interviewed by somebody who was asking me

00:18:13.566 --> 00:18:15.200
about your drive—

00:18:15.200 --> 00:18:18.700
what drives you—and I said,

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:21.066
Elon is driven to solve problems.

00:18:21.266 --> 00:18:25.566
He's driven to make life in the world better

00:18:25.566 --> 00:18:27.633
by just solving the biggest problems,

00:18:27.633 --> 00:18:29.866
over and over and over again.

00:18:29.966 --> 00:18:31.500
And if someone else were solving them,

00:18:31.500 --> 00:18:34.666
he wouldn't need to, but no one else is solving them.

00:18:34.800 --> 00:18:38.100
So I just want to say thank you for that, pal.

00:18:38.233 --> 00:18:40.133
Thank you for that. You're welcome.

00:18:45.766 --> 00:18:47.466
I am curious—

00:18:47.466 --> 00:18:49.666
do you think that democracy

00:18:49.666 --> 00:18:51.466
and our modern institutions

00:18:51.466 --> 00:18:55.200
can keep up with the supersonic tsunami coming our way?

00:18:55.400 --> 00:18:58.233
Are they just going to fall in its path?

00:18:58.233 --> 00:19:00.900
Are they just going to break down? How do we deal?

00:19:10.833 --> 00:19:12.766
I mean, it's called the singularity for a reason,

00:19:12.766 --> 00:19:13.300
you know,

00:19:13.300 --> 00:19:16.000
which is that it's hard to predict what happens in that—

00:19:16.066 --> 00:19:17.466
in the singularity, I mean.

00:19:17.600 --> 00:19:19.366
Grok's logo is the singularity.

00:19:19.366 --> 00:19:20.900
I love it. It's a beautiful logo.

00:19:20.900 --> 00:19:21.666
Behind you, by the way.

00:19:21.666 --> 00:19:22.766
It's gorgeous, yeah.

00:19:22.766 --> 00:19:23.566
Thank you.

00:19:24.266 --> 00:19:25.466
Uh, yeah.

00:19:26.433 --> 00:19:27.000
It's—

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:28.066
the light, the light—

00:19:28.266 --> 00:19:29.066
the—

00:19:29.566 --> 00:19:32.033
the halo around a black hole is

00:19:32.033 --> 00:19:33.433
mass and light falling in,

00:19:33.433 --> 00:19:34.333
that type of thing.

00:19:34.866 --> 00:19:36.233
Um, it's hard—

00:19:36.233 --> 00:19:38.566
it's hard to know what happens inside the singularity.

00:19:39.300 --> 00:19:41.666
Um, but it's going to be very interesting.

00:19:41.666 --> 00:19:42.900
Like, we're going to live in it.

00:19:42.900 --> 00:19:44.366
The future will be very entertaining.

00:19:44.400 --> 00:19:46.266
Of that, I'm confident.

00:19:46.766 --> 00:19:47.566
Um...

00:19:48.033 --> 00:19:49.000
And, uh...

00:19:50.633 --> 00:19:51.833
I think also

00:19:51.833 --> 00:19:53.700
that AI and robotics

00:19:53.700 --> 00:19:55.266
are also the only way we're going to solve

00:19:55.266 --> 00:19:56.666
our budget deficit, frankly,

00:19:56.666 --> 00:19:58.500
and not just go bankrupt as a country.

00:19:59.466 --> 00:20:01.200
Um, so...

00:20:03.700 --> 00:20:03.866
I'm—

00:20:03.866 --> 00:20:05.200
I'm, you know...

00:20:05.233 --> 00:20:06.600
You've had an influence on me in that

00:20:06.600 --> 00:20:08.966
I've just decided to be more optimistic.

00:20:08.966 --> 00:20:10.866
It's like, we just should be more optimistic.

00:20:10.866 --> 00:20:11.566
Thank you, pal.

00:20:11.566 --> 00:20:13.233
I know that I wasn't an optimist,

00:20:13.233 --> 00:20:13.866
but I was, like,

00:20:13.866 --> 00:20:16.533
maybe dwelling a little too much on the negative stuff.

00:20:16.633 --> 00:20:17.100
It's all—

00:20:17.100 --> 00:20:20.566
it's all upside being an optimist and a realist

00:20:20.566 --> 00:20:22.066
a little bit, yeah.

00:20:22.066 --> 00:20:23.733
Yeah, yeah, exactly.

00:20:24.200 --> 00:20:25.366
You don't want to be complacent

00:20:25.366 --> 00:20:27.166
or just assume everything's going to go well,

00:20:27.166 --> 00:20:28.766
but try to make it go well.

00:20:29.666 --> 00:20:30.466
Um...

00:20:31.433 --> 00:20:32.033
But I mean,

00:20:32.033 --> 00:20:34.300
there will be some pretty amazing things that happen.

00:20:34.300 --> 00:20:38.100
So if you've got humanoid robots that are

00:20:38.100 --> 00:20:41.200
that have very high dexterity and

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:43.633
and are incredibly smart,

00:20:43.633 --> 00:20:45.666
it means that everyone on Earth

00:20:45.966 --> 00:20:48.933
will have access to better medical care

00:20:49.566 --> 00:20:50.966
than—

00:20:51.266 --> 00:20:52.700
than the richest person on Earth—

00:20:52.700 --> 00:20:53.200
which, by the way,

00:20:53.200 --> 00:20:54.100
I would say, like,

00:20:54.266 --> 00:20:54.566
you know,

00:20:54.566 --> 00:20:55.833
if I'm legitimately the richest person on Earth,

00:20:55.833 --> 00:20:56.566
I think, actually,

00:20:56.566 --> 00:20:57.566
sovereigns are richer than me,

00:20:57.566 --> 00:20:58.466
by the way, but...

00:20:58.466 --> 00:20:59.666
I think so. But it's like—

00:20:59.666 --> 00:21:00.466
like, you know,

00:21:00.466 --> 00:21:00.833
I—

00:21:00.833 --> 00:21:02.200
I had to have, like,

00:21:02.200 --> 00:21:03.600
neck surgery three times

00:21:03.600 --> 00:21:06.133
because the first two were done wrong.

00:21:06.633 --> 00:21:07.866
You know, I'm like—

00:21:08.233 --> 00:21:09.100
I'm like, what the—

00:21:09.100 --> 00:21:10.933
you know, um...

00:21:11.666 --> 00:21:12.666
So...

00:21:13.833 --> 00:21:14.600
And I'm like—

00:21:14.600 --> 00:21:15.866
my back still hurts a little bit.

00:21:15.866 --> 00:21:16.666
I'm like,

00:21:17.266 --> 00:21:18.700
can AI please solve back pain?

00:21:18.700 --> 00:21:19.866
That would be a huge win.

00:21:19.866 --> 00:21:20.966
And I think it will.

00:21:22.033 --> 00:21:23.566
Yep, so...

00:21:23.566 --> 00:21:24.700
you know, back pain sucks.

00:21:24.700 --> 00:21:26.533
I think that's maybe, like—

00:21:26.800 --> 00:21:27.300
you know, sometimes,

00:21:27.300 --> 00:21:28.700
why do people get grumpy when they get older?

00:21:28.700 --> 00:21:29.900
It's because of back pain.

00:21:30.433 --> 00:21:32.100
It's like, if your back hurts all the time,

00:21:32.100 --> 00:21:33.866
you can't sleep well; you're going to be grumpy.

00:21:33.866 --> 00:21:35.533
We had—but if you...

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:38.000
We had David Sinclair on stage this morning,

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:40.566
and he's going into human trials with

00:21:40.566 --> 00:21:42.766
partial epigenetic reprogramming,

00:21:42.966 --> 00:21:44.833
and, uh, one of the—

00:21:44.833 --> 00:21:47.966
one of the papers recently published shows it

00:21:48.200 --> 00:21:49.733
enables joint repair,

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:53.500
and so back pain may be one of the things that

00:21:53.566 --> 00:21:54.933
it eliminates, so...

00:21:55.600 --> 00:21:56.800
Uh, that would be amazing.

00:21:56.833 --> 00:21:58.033
Yeah, for sure.

00:21:58.033 --> 00:21:59.366
For sure. Honestly,

00:21:59.366 --> 00:22:00.800
the average happiness level for humans

00:22:00.800 --> 00:22:02.166
would just go up tremendously

00:22:02.166 --> 00:22:03.066
if you just solve back pain,

00:22:03.066 --> 00:22:05.100
because it's not a question of

00:22:05.766 --> 00:22:07.600
if you'll get back pain—it's when.

00:22:07.666 --> 00:22:09.000
You know you'll get back pain.

00:22:09.800 --> 00:22:10.233
I...

00:22:10.233 --> 00:22:12.133
I keep on saying it's not a good design.

00:22:12.166 --> 00:22:14.233
I keep on inviting you to come down to Fountain Life in

00:22:14.233 --> 00:22:14.966
in, uh...

00:22:14.966 --> 00:22:16.366
in Dallas. We'll, uh...

00:22:16.400 --> 00:22:18.566
we'll help you out sometime, when you have time.

00:22:18.566 --> 00:22:18.900
Okay, well—

00:22:18.900 --> 00:22:20.166
do you have—like, what do you...

00:22:20.166 --> 00:22:21.100
I understand, like,

00:22:21.100 --> 00:22:23.266
you can get, like, MRI and CAT scans and everything,

00:22:23.266 --> 00:22:24.300
but, like, what do you do with that?

00:22:24.300 --> 00:22:25.300
You know, it's like—

00:22:26.400 --> 00:22:27.900
